HW 3 - Working with gapminder Data

In this assignment you will start playing around a little more with gapminder (This is the dataset we used to explain ggplot function). You can try each of these explorations with geom_point() and then with geom_smooth(), or both together. Please use Healy_CH3.R, as the base, to work around.

    1. What happens when you put the geom_smooth() function before geom_point() instead of after it in Healy_CH3.R? What does this tell you about how the plot is drawn? Think about how this might be useful when drawing plots. When geom_smooth() is put in front of geom_point() , The smoothe curve falls behind the data points.

    1. Instead of mapping color = year in part d, what happens if you try color = factor(year)? There is now a different color representing each year in the dataset, rather than different shades of blue representing different decades, which I believe visualizes the data more effectively.
# place appropriate r syntaxes to draw part e plot
p <- ggplot(data = gapminder,
            mapping = aes(x = gdpPercap,
                          y = lifeExp,
                          color = year))
p + geom_point() +
  geom_smooth(method = "loess") +
  scale_x_log10()
## `geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ x'

p + geom_point(mapping = aes(color = factor(year))) +
  scale_x_log10()
